pageContext.claim: “Autos, China -- you have a 15 percent tariff, and the U.S. has 2.5. So when you sell -- and, by the way, we got the autos down from 40 in China. I got them down to 15. But it's still 15 percent versus 2.5 percent. But, if you know, it was 40 and 25 percent.”
pageContext.analysis: The tariff in China on U.S. car imports is 15 percent — down from 25 percent. But it's worth remembering that General Motors sells more cars in China (3.9 million) than in the US (3 million) and saw its China business grow 13 percent in 2016.
